## Key Concepts I Learned

To secure access to Microsoft Entra ID, Microsoft recommends a Zero Trust approach centered on strong authentication, least-privilege access, and continuous monitoring. Key steps include:

Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for all users, especially administrators. Prefer phishing-resistant methods such as passkeys, Windows Hello for Business, or FIDO2 security keys where possible.
Use Conditional Access policies to control sign-ins based on user identity, device compliance, location, application, and risk level. Block or require additional verification for risky sign-ins


## Lab / Hands-On Work

### What I did

Sign in to the Microsoft Entra admin center with an account that has the appropriate administrator role (such as Conditional Access Administrator or Security Administrator).
Navigate to Conditional Access
Go to Protection → Conditional Access.
Select Create new policy.
Name the policy
Give the policy a descriptive name, such as Require MFA for Admins.
Assign users or groups
Select the users, groups, or directory roles the policy applies to.
Exclude emergency ("break-glass") administrator accounts to avoid accidental lockout.
Select target resources
Choose the cloud apps or actions the policy will protect (for example, Microsoft 365, Azure Management, or all cloud apps).
Configure conditions (optional)
Apply the policy based on factors such as:
Device platform (Windows, macOS, iOS, Android)
Location (trusted or untrusted networks)
Client applications
Sign-in risk
User risk
Device state
Choose access controls
Decide whether to:
Grant access
Block access
If granting access, require one or more controls, such as:
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
A compliant deviceand supporting the Principle of Least Privilege.

